result.execSummary:
The defendant Caitlen M Kennedy was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/ Intent-Amphetamine(>10-50g), a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(e)3.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Partial Transcript - Plea & Sentencing held 5-13-15 w/ SLH - filed by Michelle Stello

10:09 AM - Def in court, in custody.  Michelle Ann Keller appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Crt: you were reported as a result of violations. 
Def: I had a lot of violations and it's hard for me to start where they all started. Last Sat I relapsed and used and that' the biggest one for me. I had just been avoiding going into a hosp cuz I was sick but I was trying to avoid a Dx that I was going to get. I let my bracelet die. There are things I shouldn't have lied about. I am still getting used to and trying to understand you are trying to help me. I keep pushing the help away. I hope this time when I get out I am excited to start over and really put in an effort. Last time I didn't think it would take much to beat the addiction but I was wrong. 
Crt: if you sneak out of the facility, get drugs and lie you will be expelled and unless the violations are extremely minor, and to date, they have not, you are building a strong case for sig time in prison. What has shocked me has been your attitude, the deceit to those who are trying to help you. You will be released at 6 AM Sat 6/27 and will be on lock down on Ophelia's house until 6 AM on Monday 6/29. While on lock down want you to take a look at the partial trans of your sentencing and I want you to read that and the explanations you gave and the commitments you made at the time of sentence and prepare a written document on your comments at sentencing and we will discuss that next week at DC. The goal is for you to get back in touch w/ your state of mind at sentencing and I wonder if you were sincere then or just saying those things b/c they might lead to a lighter sentence. If that's the case you will go to prison. The key to prison is in your hands and at this point you are doing everything possible to open those doors.
